Cell surface receptors, including EGFR, FGFR, VEGFR, and gp130, mediate the activation of STAT3 by growth factors and cytokines [4]. Targeting these growth factor/cytokine receptors has been shown to be an effective strategy to inhibit aberrant STAT3 activation [17]. Most of current EGFR inhibitors, such as gefitinib, erlotinib, and afatinib, target the ATP-binding site of the kinases [54,55]. However, the emergence of drug resistance calls for therapeutic agents with alternative mechanisms of action. For example, T790M and C979S mutations in EGFR were reported to be the leading mechanism of resistance to traditional EGFR inhibitors [56,57]. Recently, Jia et al. identified EAI001 (Fig. 2
                     ) as an allosteric and non-ATP competitive inhibitor that targets the selected drug-resistant EGFRL858R/T790M mutant, but not the wild-type protein [58]. Complex structure mapping reveals that the compound binds to an allosteric pocket that is formed by outward displacement of the C-helix in the inactive conformation of the kinase. Within this allosteric pocket, EAI001 forms hydrogen bonds with Asp855 in the DFG motif, and forms hydrophobic interactions between Leu777 and Phe856 (Fig. 3
                     ). Furthermore, EAI045 (Fig. 2), a synthesized analogue of EAI001, is active and selective for monomeric EGFRT790M with IC50 values of 3 nM. When combined with cetuximab, a monoclonal antibody that can block the dimerization of EGFR, EAI045 shows a significant inhibitory effect in a mouse model of EGFRL858R/T790M-drived lung cancer [48,58]. To et al. identified another analogue of EAI001, JBJ-04-125-02 (Fig. 2), as a more potent allosteric inhibitor of the EGFR mutant (IC50 = 0.26 nM). JBJ-04-125-02, on its own, inhibits cell proliferation and cancer growth in a mouse model [59]. Altogether, these findings illustrate that targeting allosteric sites provides exciting opportunity for the development of inhibitors against mutant proteins.

Namanja et al. found an inter-domain allosteric communication in STAT3 protein using nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR). Interaction between the tyrosine phosphorylated peptide (pY-peptide) and the SH2 domain also alter the structure and dynamics of the LD and DBD domains of STAT3 protein. Consistently, a point mutation (I568F) in the LD domain, identified in a patient with autosomal-dominant hyper IgE syndrome, reduces the binding affinity of SH2 domain to the pY-peptide [92]. More recently, we demonstrated that a thiazole-derived oridonin analogue, CYD0618 (Fig. 8
                     ), covalently binds to Cys542 in the LD domain of STAT3 and specifically inhibits its phosphorylation and function. Despite binding to the LD domain, CYD0618 reduces STAT3 binding to the pY-peptide via an allosteric mechanism. Furthermore, in vitro and in vivo data showed that CYD0618 exhibited a potent anti-cancer effect in cancer cells that harbor constitutive STAT3 activation [93]. In agreement with our study, S-glutathionylation at Cys542 was found to impair JAK2-induced Tyr705 phosphorylation of STAT3 [94]. Taken together, these findings suggest that Cys542 in the LD domain and nearby regions constitute a new allosteric site (allosteric site 1, 
                     Fig. 7) for the selective inhibition of STAT3.
